reaties, the Indian Act, residential schools, the Sixties Scoop, and the drive for self-determination. Braided Learning draws on Indigenous knowledge to make sense of a difficult past, decode unjust conditions in the present, and work toward a more equitable future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous artszCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxStudy and teachingzCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxHistory. 0aMulticultural educationzCanada. 0aStorytellingzCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aDion, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311141763940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077488080040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774880800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774880800/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-141763-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles